List<DebugElement> get componentViewChildren => debugElement.componentViewChildren;
```

How to change styles in child component from parent when ViewEncapsulation.Emulated? I think it is a common thing that happens with reusable component. For example, my-button component can have different background color:
parent component:
```css
/*button color in parent component is red*/
my-button {
  background-color: red;
}
```
my button component
```css
/*button is yellow by default*/
:host {
  background-color: yellow;
}
```
Right now it doesn't work. All styles are encapsulated and can only affect components in which they are defined.

A really common pattern in Angular 2 testing is to wrap the entire `it` callback in `injectAsync`. I think that can be sugarized a bit. It can also be a good solution against abusive indentation coming from `clang-format`.

```
it('should show 10 stars by default', injectAsync([TestComponentBuilder], (tcb) => {
     return tcb.createAsync(NgbRating).then((fixture) => {
       fixture.detectChanges();

       const compiled = fixture.debugElement.nativeElement;

       const stars = getStars(compiled);
       expect(stars.length).toBe(10);
     });
   }));
```

Martin at `clang-format` suggested to use a wrapper like:

```
function itIj(msg: string, ...componentOrFn: Function[]) {
  let injectables = componentOrFn.slice(0, -1);
  let testFn = componentOrFn.slice(-1)[0];
  it(msg, injectables, testFn);
}
```

I am not fond of having wrappers like that in my codebase (to workaround a formatter), but since Angular desperately needs lot of sugar around testing, I think this is a good candidate.

Check angular/clang-format#20 for more information.

Cheers.

See this [demo repo](https://github.com/jhades/ng2-issue-parent-cannot-see-child) for reproducing the issue (present in alpha-45).

If we have a parent directive with several child directives present:

    <div parent-directive>
        <div *ng-for="#child of childs;">
            <div child-directive>{{child}}</div>
        </div>
    </div>

And we try to inject the childs in the parent using `@Query`:

    @Directive({
        selector: '[parent-directive]'
    })
    export class ParentDirective {
        childs = [];
       
       constructor(@Query(ChildDirective) childs: QueryList<ChildDirective>) {
           console.log("building parent directive");
           childs.changes.toRx().subscribe(() => {
               // this array always has size zero, it should be 3
               this.childs = childs.toArray(); 
           });
        }
    }

The childs list is always empty. This is because the childs are trying to have the parent injected using `@Host`:

    @Directive({
        selector: '[child-directive]'
    })
    export class ChildDirective {

        constructor(@Host(ParentDirective) parent: ParentDirective) {
            console.log("building child directive with injected parent.");
        }
    }

If we remove the `@Host` injection, the query then returns several elements as expected.

The issue can be reproduced with this repo -> https://github.com/jhades/ng2-issue-parent-cannot-see-child
